00:48:10,273 --> 00:48:18,273
(♪ Orchestra dramatically restates
the guitar theme)

494
00:52:47,926 --> 00:52:52,718
Rise, oh, rise.
Oh, surely thou shalt rise.

495
00:52:52,889 --> 00:52:54,716
But not before the opening

496
00:52:54,891 --> 00:52:57,596
of the Metropolitan Cathedral
of Christ the King,

497
00:52:57,769 --> 00:53:01,102
inaugurated by Cardinal Heenan
in his brand new frock -

498
00:53:01,272 --> 00:53:04,143
the Vatican's response to Schiaparelli.

499
00:53:05,193 --> 00:53:09,273
I had lived my spiritual and religious life
under popes Pius Xll,

500
00:53:09,447 --> 00:53:12,567
John XXlll
and Clitoris the umpteenth,

501
00:53:12,742 --> 00:53:15,233
which is enough to turn anyone pagan.

502
00:53:15,412 --> 00:53:18,827
As far as I knew, Holy Mother Church
still wanted me.

503
00:53:18,998 --> 00:53:21,572
But I no longer wanted her.

504
00:53:21,751 --> 00:53:26,330
For I was now a very happy,
very contented, born again atheist.

505
00:53:26,506 --> 00:53:28,415
Thank God!

506
00:53:29,467 --> 00:53:33,631
O come, all ye faithful.
Have another plateful.

507
00:53:35,265 --> 00:53:40,686
(♪ Mahler: Symphony No. 2
The Resurrection )

508
00:53:50,447 --> 00:53:56,948
(♪ Subdued, unaccompanied
voices reverberate deeply)

509
00:55:46,104 --> 00:55:51,727
(♪ Slowly rising brass chorale builds
to exhilarating climax)

510
00:57:01,387 --> 00:57:07,176
(♪ Chorus sings with hushed voices)

511
00:58:19,674 --> 00:58:27,674
(♪ Voices rise, defiant and resilient)

512
00:59:18,858 --> 00:59:22,393
Municipal architecture.
Dispiriting at the best of times,

513
00:59:22,570 --> 00:59:26,402
but when combined with
the British genius for creating the dismal,

514
00:59:26,574 --> 00:59:30,785
makes for a cityscape
which is anything but Elysian.

515
00:59:34,123 --> 00:59:40,244
(♪ Brahms: Lullaby,
sung by Jennifer John)

516
01:00:31,764 --> 01:00:36,509
Out to sea, the dawn wind
wrinkles and slides.

517
01:00:37,603 --> 01:00:42,016
I am here, or elsewhere.

518
01:00:42,191 --> 01:00:45,477
In my end is my beginning.

519
01:00:48,239 --> 01:00:55,120
"We meet our destiny on the road
we take to avoid it.' [Carl Jung]

520
01:00:58,040 --> 01:01:03,283
I said to my soul, be still
and let the dark come upon you

521
01:01:03,462 --> 01:01:06,547
which shall be the darkness of God.

522
01:01:06,716 --> 01:01:11,294
I said to my soul, be still
and wait without hope,

523
01:01:11,470 --> 01:01:14,044
for hope would be hope
for the wrong thing.

524
01:01:14,223 --> 01:01:18,007
Wait without love, for love
would be love of the wrong thing.

525
01:01:18,186 --> 01:01:20,012
There is yet faith.

526
01:01:20,188 --> 01:01:24,019
But the faith, the love and the hope
are all in the waiting -

527
01:01:24,192 --> 01:01:27,395
the rest is not our business -

528
01:01:27,570 --> 01:01:29,812
at the still point of the turning world,

529
01:01:29,989 --> 01:01:34,117
suspended in time
between pole and tropic.

530
01:01:34,285 --> 01:01:37,369
And all is always now.

531
01:01:37,538 --> 01:01:39,994
Home is where one starts from.

532
01:01:40,166 --> 01:01:43,036
As we grow older,
the world becomes stranger,

533
01:01:43,211 --> 01:01:47,078
the pattern more complicated
of dead and living.

534
01:01:47,256 --> 01:01:49,926
There is a time for the evening
under starlight;

535
01:01:50,092 --> 01:01:55,169
a time for the evening under lamplight;
the evening with the photograph album.

536
01:01:55,348 --> 01:02:00,888
Love is most nearly itself
when here and now cease to matter.

537
01:02:01,062 --> 01:02:04,929
I said to my soul, be still

538
01:02:05,107 --> 01:02:09,816
and accept this, my chanson d'amour
for all that has passed.

539
01:02:09,987 --> 01:02:13,902
But where, oh, where are you
the Liverpool I knew and loved?

540
01:02:14,075 --> 01:02:16,648
Where have you gone without me?

541
01:02:16,827 --> 01:02:21,074
And now I'm an alien in my own land.

542
01:02:21,249 --> 01:02:24,783
"O Tempora o mores.'

543
01:02:24,961 --> 01:02:28,495
Oh, the times, oh, the fashions.

544
01:02:29,840 --> 01:02:33,541
Tread gently, stranger
as you softly turn the key

545
01:02:33,719 --> 01:02:39,093
To unlock time and cause the years
to fall towards their end

546
01:02:39,267 --> 01:02:42,600
Speak low, Love, but speak wisely

547
01:02:42,770 --> 01:02:46,139
For frail time hangs by a thread
above the world

548
01:02:46,315 --> 01:02:49,435
With only hope to keep us safe

549
01:02:49,610 --> 01:02:54,568
Tap lightly at the door,
then close it with a silent shock

550
01:02:54,740 --> 01:02:58,904
But never, ever yield to the night

551
01:03:01,789 --> 01:03:05,869
(♪ Faure: Dolly Suite )

552
01:03:13,384 --> 01:03:19,339
(♪ Piano plays nursery song)

553
01:04:49,522 --> 01:04:52,973
We shall return with hope
to the good earth.

554
01:04:53,943 --> 01:04:59,447
And you, my dear children,
you are the earth.

555
01:05:07,873 --> 01:05:12,037
But, I reason earth is short

556
01:05:12,211 --> 01:05:14,453
And anguish absolute

557
01:05:14,630 --> 01:05:17,203
And many hurt

558
01:05:17,383 --> 01:05:19,210
But what of that?

559
01:05:21,929 --> 01:05:24,716
I reason, we could die:

560
01:05:24,890 --> 01:05:29,552
The best vitality cannot excel decay

561
01:05:29,728 --> 01:05:32,564
But what of that?

562
01:05:33,274 --> 01:05:37,106
I reason that in heaven,
somehow it will be even

563
01:05:37,278 --> 01:05:40,481
Some new equation given

564
01:05:41,824 --> 01:05:43,900
But what of that?

565
01:05:44,076 --> 01:05:50,613
(♪ Horn note sings out)

566
01:06:13,856 --> 01:06:17,023
(Bells chime)

567
01:06:35,085 --> 01:06:37,707
We shall not cease from exploration.

568
01:06:37,880 --> 01:06:42,043
And the end of all our exploring
will be to arrive where we started

569
01:06:42,218 --> 01:06:44,755
and to know the place for the first time.

570
01:06:45,554 --> 01:06:47,761
Through the unknown remembered gate,

571
01:06:47,932 --> 01:06:52,475
when the last of earth left to discover
is that which was the beginning.

572
01:06:52,645 --> 01:06:58,434
A condition of complete simplicity
costing not less than everything.

573
01:06:58,943 --> 01:07:01,398
And all shall be well

574
01:07:01,570 --> 01:07:06,612
And all manner of thing
shall be well.

575
01:07:13,457 --> 01:07:15,829
If all the world and Love were young

576
01:07:16,001 --> 01:07:18,575
And truth in every shepherd's tongue

577
01:07:18,754 --> 01:07:21,459
These pretty pleasures might me move

578
01:07:21,632 --> 01:07:24,835
To live with thee, and be thy love

579
01:07:25,010 --> 01:07:28,545
But time drives flocks from field to fold

580
01:07:28,722 --> 01:07:31,474
When rivers rage and rocks grow cold

581
01:07:31,642 --> 01:07:34,215
And Philomel becometh dumb

582
01:07:34,395 --> 01:07:37,396
The rest complains of cares to come

583
01:07:37,940 --> 01:07:44,192
The flowers do fade, and wanton fields
to wayward winter reckoning yields

584
01:07:44,363 --> 01:07:46,984
A honey tongue, a heart of gall

585
01:07:47,157 --> 01:07:50,740
Is Fancy's spring but Sorrow's fall

586
01:07:50,911 --> 01:07:54,363
Thy gowns, thy shoes,
thy beds of roses

587
01:07:54,873 --> 01:07:58,040
Thy cap, thy kirtle, and thy posies

588
01:07:58,210 --> 01:08:02,539
Soon break, soon wither,
soon forgotten

589
01:08:02,715 --> 01:08:06,712
In folly ripe, in reason rotten

590
01:08:06,885 --> 01:08:09,258
Thy belt of straw and ivy buds

591
01:08:09,430 --> 01:08:12,466
Thy coral clasps and amber studs

592
01:08:12,641 --> 01:08:15,975
All those in me no means can move

593
01:08:16,145 --> 01:08:19,311
To come to thee and be thy love

594
01:08:19,481 --> 01:08:22,981
But could youth last and love still breed

595
01:08:23,152 --> 01:08:26,817
Had joys no date nor age no need

596
01:08:26,989 --> 01:08:30,737
Then those delights
my mind might move

597
01:08:30,909 --> 01:08:35,121
To live with thee and be thy love

598
01:08:40,919 --> 01:08:42,995
We are being gathered in...

599
01:08:44,256 --> 01:08:47,043
...at gloaming.

600
01:08:54,808 --> 01:08:57,180
Is it sleep?

601
01:08:57,353 --> 01:09:00,057
Or is it death?

602
01:09:00,856 --> 01:09:06,313
(Mahler: Resurrection,
triumphant chorus sings)

603
01:11:24,249 --> 01:11:26,705
Goodnight, ladies.

604
01:11:26,877 --> 01:11:30,460
Goodnight, sweet ladies.

605
01:11:30,631 --> 01:11:32,041
Goodnight.

606
01:11:32,633 --> 01:11:33,961
Goodnight.

607
01:11:34,802 --> 01:11:37,043
Goodnight.

608
01:11:39,056 --> 01:11:43,516
(♪ Liszt:
Consolation No.3 In D Flat Major)
